            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Mark is distinguished from Matthew in this respect, that the latter represents Jesus as laying the theological problem before ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the assembled Pharisees",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and then relates that they were ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "thereby",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " brought to silence, so that they put no further questions to Him; whereas Mark relates that ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the conversation as to the most important commandment",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " had had this result, and thereafter Jesus had thrown out ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "before the people",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", while He was teaching (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 12:37",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 12:35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), the question respecting the Son of David.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀποκριθείς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The following question to the people is a reply—publicly exposing the theological helplessness of the scribes—to the silence, to which they had just seen themselves reduced by the very fact that one of their number had even given his entire approval to Jesus. The scribes are still present. But it is not to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "themselves",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " that Jesus puts His question; He utters it before the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "people",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but in express ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "reference",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "γραμματεῖς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". They may therefore give information also before the people, if they can. If they cannot, they stand there the more completely vanquished and put to shame. And they cannot, because to them the divine lineage of the Messiah, in virtue of which as David’s descendant He is yet David’s Lord, remained veiled and unperceived;—we may conceive after ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "πόθεν υἱὸς αὐτοῦ ἐστιν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "pause",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of this silence and this confusion. So peculiar is this whole position of the matter in Mark, that it appears to be (in opposition to Hilgenfeld and Baur) original.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
